<H3> <TI>   No Talks Held 28 Jun </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    No Talks Held 28 Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2806142694 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
1200 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2806142694 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] No session of the peace talks was held in Lusaka, 
Zambia, today. 
  Mediator Alioune Blondin Beye is presently examining 
documents received from the government and the National Union 
for the Total Independence of Angola [UNITA] connected with the 
implementation of modalities for national reconciliation. Alves 
Antonio reports: 
  The mediator in the Angolan peace process has changed his 
tactic. He is currently examining the documents from the 
government and UNITA connected with the implementation of 
modalities for national reconciliation, so as to come up with a 
compromise which will serve as a foundation for the 
negotiations. Thus, the representatives of the government and 
UNITA remain on alert in their hotels. 
  President Frederick Chiluba is expect to receive Alioune 
Blondin Beye today to discuss issues connected with the Angolan 
peace process. 
  Meanwhile, members of opposition parties from the 
extra-parliamentary group began the day well. They were 
received by Ambassador (Rocha Pares), representing the troika of 
observers in the Angolan peace process, and they gave him a 
proposal which they consider as an alternative for the present 
peace talks. Thereafter, they met with government 
representatives. At the end of the meeting, the spokesman for 
the extra-parliamentary group spoke to the reporting team of the 
Angolan National Radio. 
  [Begin unidentified official recording] Today, 28 June, we 
also held a meeting with the government team. We presented our 
plan and they briefed us on ongoing discussions. We saw a 
certain understanding, a clear optimism on the side of the 
government, and thus we think that the process is on the right 
track. We encouraged the team to continue with this conduct so 
that peace can be found as soon as possible, since many people 
are dying in Angola. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

