<H3> <TI>   Government, UNITA Approve National Reconciliation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government, UNITA Approve National Reconciliation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2706203894 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
1900 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2706203894 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Negotiating teams from the government and the 
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola [UNITA] 
today approved specific principles for the implementation of 
modalities for national reconciliation. As is normally the 
case, in its attempt to hinder the peace talks, UNITA wants to 
introduce new elements in the issue connected with Jonas 
Savimbi's status which has already been discussed and has 
received the consensus of all parties. Our correspondent Alves 
Antonio reports. 
  Negotiating teams from the government and UNITA have finally 
approved specific principles for national reconciliation which, 
among other things, include the issue of installations for Jonas 
Savimbi's organization. Thus, the government and UNITA are now 
able to tackle practical issues in the implementation of 
modalities for national reconciliation which include the major 
guidelines and a future government of national unity. 
  Surprisingly, UNITA spokesman Jorge Valentim said and we 
quote, it is not necessary to have a special status for 
President Savimbi, unquote. Meanwhile, regarding this issue, 
the government version is different in that Savimbi's status has 
already been discussed and approved. What UNITA now wanted was 
to introduce new changes. This being the case, the government 
is demanding from UNITA a written document saying that it wants 
to withdraw this issue from the dossier. 

</TEXT>

