<H3> <TI>   NPFL: `Scheme' To Thwart Nigerian Demands Exposed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NPFL: `Scheme' To Thwart Nigerian Demands Exposed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB2906164694 Gbarnga Radio ELRL in English 1400 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB2906164694 </F>
<F P=104>  Gbarnga Radio ELRL </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] An orchestrated propaganda scheme being developed in 
Monrovia by a gang of Communist-minded individuals, to divert 
international attention and counter continued calls by former 
President Taylor for the total and unconditional withdrawal of 
the Nigerian contingent of ECOMOG [Economic Community of West 
African States Cease-Fire Monitoring Group] and move towards the 
establishment of a national army, has been exposed. A series of 
[word indistinct] activities, with the backing of the local BBC 
correspondent -- who is an ECOMOG paid agent in Monrovia -- sent 
panicky waves of fear in Monrovia and elsewhere of an imminent 
war, despite calls for the cessation of all hostilities in the 
country. The exposure of the Nigerian complicity in aiding and 
abetting splinter armed groups in Liberia, particularly, the 
Liberian Peace Council and one of ULIMO's [United Liberation 
Movement for Democracy in Liberia] factions, has led to harsh 
international criticisms and demands by local interest and 
pressure groups for the immediate and unconditional withdrawal 
of the Nigerian contingent of ECOMOG from Liberia. 

</TEXT>

