<H3> <TI>   UN Representative To Meet With Mugabe </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Representative To Meet With Mugabe </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB3006123494 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
1200 GMT 30 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB3006123494 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Alves Antonio in Lusaka] </F>
  [Text] In Lusaka, the frame of the negotiations has not 
altered. This morning, UN Special Representative Alioune 
Blondin Beye, who is mediating the Angolan peace talks, held a 
meeting with government representatives and probably yet another 
one with the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola 
[UNITA]. However, nothing concrete is known about the issues 
discussed, since there is an absolute silence around the sides 
involved in the negotiating process. Thus, the face-to-face 
meeting between the government and UNITA negotiators to discuss 
the implementation of the modalities of national reconciliation 
has once again been postponed. 
  Meanwhile, UNITA says that it intends by all means to govern 
Huambo Province. This position was reaffirmed in the Zambian 
capital during a meeting between the UNITA team and members of 
extraparliamentary opposition parties held yesterday. The 
latter said that UNITA would not mind continuing holding talks 
until the year 2,000. Meanwhile, the government and UNITA teams 
will return to Mulungushi this afternoon. Radio Nacional de 
Angola has learned from a reliable source that Chief Blondin 
Beye will leave for the city of Harare, Zimbabwe, tomorrow, to 
hold talks with President Robert Mugabe on the Angolan peace 
talk underway in the Zambian capital. 

</TEXT>

