<H3> <TI>   Savimbi Says Further UN Sanctions Not End of World </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Savimbi Says Further UN Sanctions Not End of World </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2906170894 Lisbon Radio Renascenca in Portuguese to Europe 
1400 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2906170894 </F>
<F P=104>  Lisbon Radio Renascenca </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] UNITA [National Union for the Total Independence of 
Angola] leader Jonas Savimbi has written to UN envoy Alioune 
Beye to say that sanctions against UNITA will not mean the end 
of the world. Jonas Savimbi warned the Angolan peace talks 
mediator about the possibility of the United Nations imposing 
sanctions against UNITA. 
  According to the letter delivered to Alioune Beye today, 
dated yesterday [28 June] from Huambo, Savimbi said that UNITA 
would no longer live with the fear of sanctions. UNITA 
spokesman Jorge Valentim refused to go into detail, but did not 
repudiate the possible interpretation that his letter implied 
that the UNITA leadership admitted that the talks might break 
down if renewed sanctions were imposed against the movement. 
  The letter comes at the same time as an impasse at the 
Lusaka 
talks. 

</TEXT>

