<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-126 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Mozambique </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dhlakama: Government Transferring Troops to Police </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dhlakama: Government Transferring Troops to Police </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2906193594 Maputo Radio Mozambique Network in Portuguese 
1030 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2906193594 </F>
<F P=104>  Maputo Radio Mozambique Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Jose Manuel Pio in Chimoio] </F>
  [Text] Mozambique National Resistance [Renamo] leader 
Afonso Dhlakama yesterday once again accused the Mozambique 
Liberation Front [Frelimo] government of infiltrating troops 
into the Police of the Republic of Mozambique. Dhlakama said 
that Frelimo is carrying out efforts to bolster the capacity of 
militiamen and the Rapid Intervention Police. Speaking to 
journalists on his arrival in Chimoio yesterday, President 
Joaquim Chissano said Frelimo is not bothered about the training 
of the new nonpartisan Mozambican army. He said this is 
evidenced by the failure to create the necessary conditions in 
the training centers. 
  [Begin Dhlakama recording] That is normal. That is normal. 
The Mozambican Government is not giving emphasis to this very 
important process. As you are aware, the barracks, the training 
camps have not been rehabilitated. The process is very much 
behind schedule. Instead of giving emphasis to the training of a 
nonpartisan national army, Frelimo is carrying out efforts to 
bolster the capacity of militiamen and the Rapid Intervention 
Police. It is infiltrating troops into the Mozambican police. 
This is a lamentable situation. All the same, I believe that we 
will be able to exercise our influence. [end recording] 
  The Renamo leader said the demobilization process is 
currently experiencing difficulties because the government is 
not interested in seeing things move smoothly in order to 
boycott the elections scheduled for October this year. 
[sentence as heard] 
  Meanwhile, today, the second day of his visit to Manica 
Province, President Afonso Dhlakama will carry out internal work 
with his party members, and this evening he will have a meeting 
with businessmen in the province. 
  According to his working program, he will leave tomorrow for 
Gondola District, and he will then visit the Manica Provincial 
Hospital and some companies in Chimoio. He will also hold a 
meeting with his party's technical cadres stationed here in 
Manica. 
  Yesterday the Renamo leader was honored with a friendly 
dinner on the occasion of his visit to Manica Province. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

