<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Envoy to UN Calls For `Dialogues' on DPRK Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Envoy to UN Calls For `Dialogues' on DPRK Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3105061394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0534 GMT 31 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3105061394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] United Nations, May 30 (XINHUA) -- The United 
Nations Security Council tonight called for "immediate 
consultations" between the International Atomic Energy Agency 
(IAEA) and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) on 
necessary measures for discharging nuclear fuel rods. 
  In a statement by the president of the Security Council, the 
Council "strongly urges" the DPRK only to proceed with the 
discharge operations at its 5-megawatt reactor in a manner which 
preserves the technical possibility of fuel measurements as 
required by the IAEA. 
  In a letter dated May 27 to the U.N. secretary-general, the 
IAEA said if the discharge operation at the 5-megawatt reactor 
continues at the same rate, the IAEA's opportunity to select, 
segregate and secure fuel rods for later measurements in 
accordance with IAEA standards will be lost within days. 
  The Security Council said it is "gravely concerned" by the 
IAEA's assessment. 
  The Security Council also asked the IAEA director-general to 
maintain IAEA inspectors in the DPRK to monitor activities at 
the 5-megawatt reactor. 
  During the Security Council consultation before the adoption 
of the president's statement, China's Permanent Representative 
to the U.N. Li Zhaoxing urged the IAEA and DPRK to make further 
consultations on the technical measures for monitoring the 
discharge of nuclear fuel rods and reach agreement as early as 
possible so as to ensure the continuation of nuclear safeguard 
monitoring. 
  Li reiterated China's view that the final way to solve this 
nuclear issue is by dialogues and negotiations between the 
related parties through channels that have been established, and 
all efforts by the international community should contribute to 
this goal. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-24361 </DOCNO>
