<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Denies Report of 28 May Lhasa Demonstration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman Denies Report of 28 May Lhasa Demonstration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK3005091794 Hong Kong AFP in English 0847 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> HK3005091794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 30 (AFP)--The Chinese government 
denied Monday a report by the Tibet Information Network (TIN) 
that hundreds of people had demonstrated Saturday in Lhasa, the 
Tibetan capital. 
  "No incident of this kind occurred, according to our 
information," a government spokesman for the Tibet Autonomous 
Region said by telephone. He made no other comment. 
  TIN, a London-based agency that monitors human rights and 
developments in Tibet, said Sunday that between 200 and 300 
people had protested in Lhasa against an increase in taxes for 
shopkeepers. 
  Several demonstrators were beaten up and five were arrested, 
TIN said, adding that three foreigners who witnessed the 
incident had had their passports confiscated. 
  Accounts garnered from foreign tourists who have recently 
been in Tibet say the situation in Lhasa is still very tense, 
and the Chinese police and military have high-profile 
deployments there. 
  The Chinese authorities are apparently concerned that 
anti-Chinese sentiment among Tibetans is being inflamed by 
inflation and unemployment, the sources say. 
  In May 1993, demonstrations erupted against rising prices 
and 
quickly degenerated into protests against China's occupation of 
Tibet. 
  China annexed Tibet in 1959 after crushing a 
pro-independence 
movement. 
  According to human rights organisations, hundreds of Tibetan 
dissidents are in Chinese jails, many of them arrested after a 
wave of anti-Chinese rallies in 1987. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-24391 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi104_k_94016" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-104 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   CPPCC National Committee Holds Chairmanship Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    CPPCC National Committee Holds Chairmanship Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2905114794 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0750 
GMT 27 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2905114794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 27 May (XINHUA) -- The chairmanship 
meeting of the Eighth National Committee of the Chinese People's 
Political Consultative Conference [CPPCC] held its 15th session 
in Beijing today. The session decided that the Seventh Session 
of the Eighth CPPCC Nation Committee Standing Committee will be 
held in Beijing in late June and suggested that the central 
topic for discussion in this session be agricultural problems. 
  Entrusted by Li Ruihuan, chairman of the CPPCC National 
Committee, vice chairman Ye Xuanping chaired today's session. 
  The Seventh Session of the Eighth CPPCC National Committee 
Standing Committee is going to hear reports by leading comrades 
concerned from the State Council concerning the agricultural 
situation and conditions in villages; examine and discuss the 
reports (in written form) of the Standing Committee members of 
the CPPCC National Committee on their visit to Anhui and of the 
members of the CPPCC National Committee on their visits to Henan 
and Shanxi for the inspection of agricultural production, rural 
work, and conditions of village and town enterprises; and 
examine and discuss the reports (in written form) on CPPCC 
National Committee Vice Chairman Wu Xueqian's visit to Korea and 
the delegation of CPPCC National Committee's visits to Jordan 
and Djibouti. 
  Attending today's session were vice chairmen Wu Xueqian, 
Yang 
Rudai, Wang Zhaoguo, Ngapoi Ngawang Jigme, Seypidin Aze, Hong 
Xuezhi, Qian Zhengying, Sun Fuling, Zhu Guangya, Wan Guoquan; 
and Secretary General Zhu Xun. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

