<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rong Yiren Inspects Shandong Enterprises </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rong Yiren Inspects Shandong Enterprises </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3005171394 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0636 
GMT 27 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW3005171394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Wang Jinye (3769 6651 2814)] </F>
  [Text] Jinan, 27 May (XINHUA) -- Vice President Rong Yiren 
pointed out during his recent inspection of Shandong: Large and 
medium-sized state-owned enterprises should treasure the present 
good opportunity for development, work hard to improve their 
operation, pay attention to market demand, do a good job in 
terms of capital funding, material resources, technology, 
qualified personnel, management, and quality and variety of 
products, and truly play a leading role in the national economy. 
  Rong Yiren inspected Shandong and investigated the problems 
of large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises there from 19 
to 26 May. During the inspection tour, he was accompanied 
separately by Jiang Chunyun, member of the CPC Central Committee 
Political Bureau and secretary of the Shandong Provincial CPC 
Committee; Li Chunting, deputy secretary of the provincial party 
committee and vice governor of Shandong Province; and Han Xikai, 
deputy secretary of the provincial party committee. He 
thoroughly familiarized himself with the situation of a dozen or 
so enterprises in seven cities, including the Jinan Light 
Motorcycle General Plant, the Qilu Petrochemical Corporation, 
and the Yantai Beijixing Watch General Plant. He also inspected 
the economic and technological development zones in Yantai and 
Weihai. He fully affirmed the efforts and exploration made by 
Shandong with respect to improving large and medium-sized 
state-owned enterprises, and was satisfied with Shandong's 
achievements in this regard. The present overall situation of 
large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises in Shandong is 
better than last year, though some of them still have 
difficulties. In the first four months of this year, the total 
output value of large and medium-sized enterprises in the 
province rose 15 percent over the same period of last year, 
while their combined total of profit delivery and tax payment 
increased by more than 20 percent. 
  Rong Yiren pointed out: Village and town enterprises have 
developed very rapidly and contributed to rural prosperity and 
stability and to the economy as a whole in recent years. 
Relatively speaking, large and medium-sized state-owned 
enterprises have been slower in development and suffering many 
difficulties. We should know that if large and medium-sized 
state-owned enterprises are in poor condition and fail to play a 
leading role in the economy, village and town enterprises will 
be unable to maintain a sustained and healthy development. It 
is understandable that the plant directors or managers of some 
large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises are feeling the 
pressure of difficulties. The promotion of the socialist market 
economy at present is providing large and medium-sized 
state-owned enterprises with a very good opportunity for 
development. Large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises 
have the edge in qualified personnel, technology, and equipment. 
Some successful enterprises among them have set an example. I 
believe that the cadres, workers, and staff members of large and 
medium-sized state-owned enterprises are full of confidence and 
they will work hard to make progress. 
  Rong Yiren emphatically pointed out: In order to improve 
large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises, we should take 
the road of reform to establish a modern enterprise system; we 
should carry out coordinated reforms of the hiring, income 
distribution, cadre, and other systems of the enterprises to 
build a good mechanism which conforms to the socialist market 
economy and fully arouses the enthusiasm of cadres and workers 
for production; we should seriously change the mode of operation 
of the planned economy and make great efforts to develop 
marketable products of good quality, great variety, and low cost 
according to market demand, and to eliminate inferior, outmoded 
products promptly; we should establish the notion of large-scale 
cooperation and abandon the practice of making an enterprise 
all-embracing regardless of its size; and while keeping to a 
main line of production, an enterprise should also engage in 
diversified undertakings, and in this way, it will widen its 
market and help resettle the surplus personnel resulting from 
streamlining. Of course, we should not do things beyond our 
reach, otherwise we will accomplish nothing. 
  During the inspection tour, Rong Yiren showed great concern 
about and emphasized the scientific and technological progress 
of enterprises. He said: Large enterprises should have their 
own scientific research institutes, if conditions permit; this 
is the way to accelerate the updating of products, increase the 
scientific and technological contents of products, and enhance 
competitive power in the market. Attention should be paid to 
the training of enterprise workers and staff members so as to 
improve the overall quality of enterprises. Using foreign 
capital and advanced technology, particularly high technology, 
is a good way to transform the large and medium-sized 
enterprises. However, we should deal with reliable foreign 
businessmen and guard against fraud. In the meantime, we must 
not always trail behind others; instead, we should first learn 
from others, and then make our own creations and surpass others. 
He pointed out: We should put our own scientific and 
technological achievements to good use. At present, many of 
them have not been utilized; such a situation affects the 
improvement of the quality of enterprises and their products and 
restricts scientific and technological development. 
  On the circulating-fund shortage reported by some 
enterprises, Rong Yiren pointed out: It is crucial to make 
funds circulate and to distribute them well. Since the 
state-supplied funds are limited, enterprises should mainly rely 
on society and themselves. He said: At present, the circulation 
of funds is too slow in quite a few enterprises. Enterprises 
should pay more attention to careful calculation and strict 
budgeting and to accelerating fund circulation. If they fail in 
this regard, the development of our market economy will be 
affected. The central authorities have already started to 
rectify the debt chain problem among enterprises. He emphasized: 
Enterprises must keep their word in business operations. They 
must not repudiate a debt, nor resort to dishonest practices. 
They must conduct business in an legitimate way and regard 
honesty as the best policy. Only in this way will our socialist 
market economy be vigorous and orderly. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

