<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Tieying Gives Top Prize at Government Film Awards </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Li Tieying Gives Top Prize at Government Film Awards </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3005163394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1435 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3005163394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 30 (XINHUA) -- Senior Chinese official 
Li Tieying today awarded the top prize to the film "Phoenix 
Zither" in this year's government film awards. 
  The movie depicts a group of rural teachers who persist in 
opening classes for dozens of poor children in a mountain area. 
The movie has moved audiences to tears in many Chinese cities. 
  Li is a member of the Political Bureau of the Central 
Committee of the Chinese Communist Party as well as a state 
councillor. 
  The film represents a group of works depicting heroes among 
the common people. This category of arts is likely to go over 
big here and is largely advocated by the government. 
  These works mostly center on humble figures who have the 
same 
life problems as the audience or readers. But they always find 
it a pleasure to assist others, give no thought to personal 
gains or losses, and help others restore confidence in life. 
  Other prize-winning films fall into the categories of 
historical events or ethnic issues, for example, "Chongqing 
Negotiations", which rehashes the historical meeting of Mao 
Zedong and Chiang Kai-shek. 
  Several children's films, documentary films, cartoon films 
and translated films were also given awards. 
  In addition, the film bureau recognized a feature film set 
in 
the securities market and co-produced by the Chinese mainland 
and Hong Kong. 
  The government-controlled contest was first staged in 1957 
but was suspended during the "Cultural Revolution" (1966-1976) 
when film production came to an almost complete halt. The 
contest was revived in the 1980s. 
  It reflects the government's guidelines on film production. 
In addition to the government film event, there are now two 
other major film contests in China. In the "Golden Rooster 
Awards," top works are selected by movie experts and 
professionals. Prizes in the "One Hundred Flowers Awards" are 
voted on by film audiences. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-24397 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi104_k_94022" </HT>


