<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hong Kong Economists Welcome Renewal of MFN Status </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hong Kong Economists Welcome Renewal of MFN Status </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3005164094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1556 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3005164094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hong Kong, May 30 (XINHUA) -- Hong Kong economists 
welcomed U.S. President Bill Clinton's decision to renew China's 
most favored nation (MFN) trade status for another year. 
  Xu Yongfu, a senior research fellow in the Hong Kong-Macao 
regional office of the Bank of China, said the decision to renew 
China's MFN trade status and delink human rights from trade 
issues was a pragmatic and wise option. 
  He said that the decision dispelled fears over the Sino-U.S. 
trade development and laid a foundation for the trade growth 
between China and the United States and in the world trade as a 
whole. 
  Edward Leung, chief economist of Hong Kong Trade Development 
Council, said Clinton's announcement to delink human rights from 
trade issues provided a basis for the smooth trade development 
between the two countries and is conducive to China's reentry 
into the GATT. 
  As a large number of Hong Kong manufacturers have opened 
plants in southern China and shipped their products to the 
United States, renewal of China's MFN trade status will make 
owners of these plants at ease and help increase the volume of 
re-export. 
  Benny Chiu, research manager of the China Service Ltd. of 
the 
Hong Hong Bank, said that Clinton's decision will benefit both 
the United States, a major supplier of funds to China, and 
China, a big market for U.S. investors. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

