<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hong Kong Businessmen Praise MFN Renewal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hong Kong Businessmen Praise MFN Renewal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2805113794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1111 GMT 28 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2805113794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hong Kong, May 28 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President Bill 
Clinton's decision to extend China's most favored nation [MFN] 
trading status for another year and to delink human rights from 
trade issues has been warmly received by HK [Hong Kong] 
residents, especially businessmen here. 
  Local business leaders today hailed the decision as not only 
conducive to the trade development among China, the United 
States and Hong Kong, but also conducive to China's reentry into 
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT). 
  Raymond Ch'ien Kuo-fung, chairman of the Federation of Hong 
Kong Industries, said that the decision will have positive 
impact on the economic development in the three areas, 
especially in Hong Kong. 
  Before the decision was made, some investors had taken a 
wait- and-see attitude towards investment in China, now that 
most of the uncertainties have been cleared away, investors' 
confidence in China will surely be enhanced, which, in turn, 
will benefit Hong Kong, Ch'ien said. 
  Ian A. Christie, chairman of the Hong Kong General Chamber 
of 
Commerce, believed that the renewal of China's MFN trading 
status has increased the chance for China to reenter the GATT. 
  He hoped China could get its permanent MFN trading status 
from the United States next year, which he said would benefit 
all of the three sides. 
  Henry Tang Ying-yen, vice-president of the Federation of 
Hong 
Kong Industries, expressed his welcome to President Clinton's 
announcement to delink human rights from trade issues while 
deciding to renew China's MFN trading status. 
  He said that the bilateral trade between two countries 
should 
be conducted on an equal basis, and it is never correct for one 
country to threaten the other with unfair trade conditions. 
  Meanwhile, many local public figures have also expressed 
their concerns over the U.S. decision to ban the import of 
Chinese weapons. 

</TEXT>

