<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shanghai Opens First Sino-Foreign Supermarket </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shanghai Opens First Sino-Foreign Supermarket </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2805155994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1503 GMT 28 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2805155994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, May 28 (XINHUA) -- A Sino-Japanese 
supermarket was launched here today, the first Sino-foreign 
joint venture of its kind set up in Shanghai. 
  The store, a joint venture between Japan's noted retail 
company Yaohan, and the Shanghai Liannong Inc., cost 300,000 
U.S. dollars and sells foodstuffs, clothes and other daily 
consumer goods, some being imported from Japan, company 
officials said. 
  Feng Guoqin, vice-secretary-general of the Shanghai 
Municipal 
Government, said the supermarket demonstrated that overseas 
businesses will be allowed a share in developing local chain 
supermarkets. 
  An official from Yaohan said today that the company has set 
up a China department to supervise its development in China. 
  The Yaohan-Lian Co. plans to set up five more chain 
supermarkets in Shanghai in two years, sources said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

