<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shanghai Telephone Information Service Marks Anniversary </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shanghai Telephone Information Service Marks Anniversary </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3005144294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1242 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3005144294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, May 30 (XINHUA) -- A hundred thousand 
callers per day dial 168 for Shanghai's telephone information 
service -- and most of the callers want information about 
banking or sex. 
  The round-the-clock service is about to celebrate its first 
birthday -- and a survey has shown which section is most 
consulted by the public. 
  The service was set up in June last year by the municipal 
telecommunications bureau. 
  When a caller dials 168, he or she hear a recording listing 
the numbers for the available subjects. A second call will 
provide recorded information on that topic. 
  The list includes general knowledge on psychology, sex, 
family, banking, foreign exchange, stocks and shares, mainland 
entry and exit formalities, and a special service for foreigners. 
  "Most of the daily 100,000 calls were for banking 
information 
and general knowledge about sex," said Chen Qiang, deputy head 
of the center said. 
  "This indicates the rise of Shanghai people's sense of 
banking and investment. Nowadays, more and more people who are 
embarrassed to ask for sex general knowledge face to face with 
the experts like to make a phone call," he said. 
  Chen said that Shanghai was the third city after Nanhai 
city, 
Guangdong Province, and Haikou, capital of Hainan Province, to 
open such a phone service, which has been praised by residents, 
the municipal government and experts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-24427 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi104_o_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-104 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Shanghai University Merges Four Former Universities </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Shanghai University Merges Four Former Universities </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2705162194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1446 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2705162194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, May 27 (XINHUA) -- The new Shanghai 
University, merging four previous universities in the city, was 
officially launched today. 
  The four forming the new university are the Shanghai 
Polytechnical University, Shanghai University of Science and 
Technology, Shanghai Science and Technology School and the 
original Shanghai University. 
  Chinese President Jiang Zemin personally calligraphed the 
new 
university's name-board. 
  Qian Weichang, noted Chinese scientist and vice-chairman of 
the National Committee of the Chinese People's Political 
Consultative Conference, was made the first president of the 
university. 
  Speaking at today's ceremony, Qian said that graduates of 
the 
new university should be patriots, people of high morality and 
noble hearts first of all, and then people of knowledge. 
  The new university will combine schools of science, 
technology, literature, arts, law, business and management in 
one. It will have 7,700 teachers and support staff, and close 
to 17,000 students, the largest among higher education 
establishments in Shanghai, said university officials. 
  The new university will have eight campuses totalling nearly 
100 ha., and college buildings totalling 610,000 sq.m. in floor 
space, the officials added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

