<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Guangxi Attracts More Overseas Investment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Guangxi Attracts More Overseas Investment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3005165694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1322 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3005165694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Nanning, May 30 (XINHUA) -- Southwest China's 
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region utilized foreign funds of 120 
million U.S. dollars in the first quarter this year, up 56 
percent over the same period in 1993. 
  According to Lei Aizu, official in charge of opening 
affairs, 
overseas money has now turned to industry, agriculture and 
infrastructures from real estate and tourism, which were hot 
spots in recent years. 
  Industrial and farming projects accounted for 69 percent of 
the 239 foreign-funded enterprises newly approved in the last 
quarter. 
  Ten of them have been invested with over 10 million U.S. 
dollars each. 
  Lei said that 80 percent of the newly-approved projects are 
funded by investors from Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan. 
  He also noted that foreign investors have started to expand 
their businesses into the mountainous areas. 
  At the beginning of this year, a special committee led by 
the 
region's top officials was set up to promote investment from 
abroad. 
  The region's growth of foreign investment in 1993 topped the 
list among the provinces in China's coastal areas. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-24434 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi104_p_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-104 </AU>
