<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Strength of Hubei's Private Sector Economy Increases </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Strength of Hubei's Private Sector Economy Increases </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2805023994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0201 GMT 28 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2805023994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Wuhan, May 28 (XINHUA) -- There is a rush among many 
people to join the private economy in central China's province 
of Hubei. 
  More and more people from government departments, colleges, 
institutions and state-run enterprises are "plunging into the 
sea of business", as the Chinese expression for joining the 
private economy goes. 
  By the end of March this year the number of private 
enterprises and individually-run firms had reached 95,173, 
employing 196,800 people. They have produced a total value of 
1.83 billion yuan so far, a 43 percent increase over the same 
period of last year. 
  The Wuhan city government has taken the economic growth in 
private sector as an important part of the reform in recent 
years. To make it work better, the government has drawn up a 
series of regulations and policies, urging government 
departments at all levels to turn on the green light for the 
registration, land use, personnel recruitment and money raising 
of private and individual enterprises. 
  Now, most of the new private businesses can get their 
licences within two or three days. 
  The development of the private economy not only provides 
jobs 
for both surplus staff of government departments and the 
unemployed, but also makes a great contribution to the 
development of the whole local economy. 

</TEXT>

