<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Ruihuan Praises Wan Li Book on Construction </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Li Ruihuan Praises Wan Li Book on Construction </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3005163894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1454 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3005163894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 30 (XINHUA) -- Chinese leader Li 
Ruihuan said here today that long-term interests and the 
environment should be emphasized in city construction. 
  Addressing the gathering for the first publication of the 
book "Wan Li's talks on city construction", Li, member of the 
Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the Chinese 
Communist Party Central Committee, said faults are likely to 
emerge with the fast growth of the economy and the speeding up 
of city construction. 
  The book, made up of 48 talks on city construction by 
China's 
former Minister of Construction Wan Li, was praised by Li as a 
"summary of lessons and experiences of China's 40 years of city 
construction." 
  Li cited the publication of the book as "a great event", 
saying that all leaders in charge of city construction should 
read it in earnest. 
  He said that there are some leaders who know little about 
city construction and never listen to other's criticisms with an 
open mind. 
  He pointed out that in some cities, many high buildings are 
arranged inappropriately, too much outside decoration is used on 
high buildings, the colors of some buildings are not in harmony, 
and the green areas are scrappy and scattered. 
  "Some faults in city construction can not be redressed until 
long after the fact, if ever," Li warned. 
  He called on city leaders and managers summing up historical 
experience and prudently handling various issues in city 
construction. 
  China had more than 570 cities by 1993, with 32 extra-large 
cities each with a population of over one million, 36 big cities 
each with a population of 500,000 to one million, 161 
middle-sized cities with 200,000 to 500,000 people, and 341 
small cities with a population of no more than 200,000. 

</TEXT>

