<H3> <TI>   Sichuan Seeks To Increase Pork Exports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sichuan Seeks To Increase Pork Exports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2805022094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0138 GMT 28 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2805022094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chengdu, May 27 (XINHUA) -- Southwest China's 
Sichuan Province, the largest pork producer in China, marketed 
18.1 million head of pigs in the first three months of this year. 
  Making up one third of the total pork output of the country, 
Sichuan supplied other provinces with about one million tons of 
pork last year. 
  As pig raising is profitable, more and more farmers are 
taking to it. At present, more than 60 percent of the local 
farmers' cash revenue comes from sales of pigs. 
  Meanwhile, the local government has drawn up favorable 
policies to encourage the farmers to raise more pigs and 
popularize new technology in this field. Twenty counties have 
been chosen to be built into lean pork export bases. 
  The province is also paying attention to pork processing and 
trading in a bid to improve economic efficiency. 

</TEXT>

