<H3> <TI>   Report on Economic Reform in Tibet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Report on Economic Reform in Tibet </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK3005144494 Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE in Chinese 1045 
GMT 30 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK3005144494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Beijing To Allow Tibet To Open More to the Outside World" </F>
-- ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE headline] 
  [Excerpt] The central government has in the past 40 years 
invested a total of 20 billion yuan in the Tibet Autonomous 
Region, establishing there a situation of economic development, 
stability, ethnic solidarity, and social progress. In 1993, 
Tibet's GDP was 3.05 billion yuan, its peasants' per-capita 
income 521 yuan, and there was relatively rapid development in 
the region's agriculture, animal husbandry, industry, 
infrastructure, and foreign trade. 
  Gyaincain Norbu, Tibet Autonomous Regional People's 
Government chairman, said at the National People's Congress 
session in mid-May: "1994 has been a critical year for our 
region in that it has seen comprehensive reforms, wholesale 
progress, key breakthroughs, and stepped-up efforts at creating 
a socialist market economic system." Regarding reforms, "efforts 
are under way to install a mechanism for the transfer of user's 
rights to land and pasture with compensation" and to encourage 
peasants and herdsmen to open up wasteland by "granting the 
operating rights to whoever opens up the land"; and 
manufacturing enterprises are transforming their operating 
mechanisms and rationalizing their business organization. 
Regarding opening up, Tibet has been exploiting its proximity 
to the border. It is improving its border ports, initiating 
cooperation with neighboring countries in many areas, improving 
the investment environment to attract more foreign and domestic 
investment, cooperating further with enterprises from the rest 
of the country to build more joint export bases, developing 
tourism, and so on. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

