<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Visit of Former Soviet Prime Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Visit of Former Soviet Prime Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    President Li Receives Ryzhkov </H4>

<F P=102> OW3005084494 Taipei CNA in English 0700 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3005084494 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sofia Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 30 (CNA) -- The Republic of China [ROC] 
hopes to develop substantive ties with all friendly, democratic 
countries in a pragmatic manner, President Li Teng-hui said 
Monday [30 May]. 
  Li made the statement while meeting with Nikolay I. Ryzhkov, 
a former prime minister of the now defunct Soviet Union, who is 
currently on a week-long visit here. 
  After more than 40 years of development, Li said, Taiwan has 
emerged as an economic powerhouse in East Asia. 
  "We are willing to share our experience in economic 
development with other countries," Li told his guest. 
  For years, Li said, Taiwan has also provided financial aid 
for many developing countries as part of its effort to return 
what it has received from the international community during its 
development process. 
  With the demise of communism, Li said he believes civilian 
exchanges between Taiwan and Russia will grow steadily in the 
years ahead. 
  Ryzhkov said he was impressed by the social stability and 
economic prosperity here. "I hope relations between our two 
countries can be further strengthened," he added. 
  Ryzhkov told Li he has joined with several Taiwan and 
Russian 
politicians and businessmen to form a permanent organization to 
boost economic, cultural and technological cooperation between 
the two countries. The new body is called the Republic of China 
and Russia International Association for Humanitarian Dialogue. 
  Li said he appreciates Ryzhkov's effort to help forge 
Taipei-Moscow ties by creating the new dialogue channel. 
"Increased civilian exchanges will lay a foundation for our 
future cooperation," he added. 

</TEXT>

