<H3> <TI>   Cross-Strait Travel Security Negotiations Proposed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cross-Strait Travel Security Negotiations Proposed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2805141994 Taipei CNA in English 1328 GMT 28 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2805141994 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Flor Wang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 28 (CNA) -- The Taipei-based Straits 
Exchange Foundation (SEF) on Saturday [28 May] sent a written 
message to Mainland China's Association for Relations Across the 
Taiwan Strait (ARATS) proposing negotiations be held in early 
June between the two sides on cross-strait travel security. 
  SEF, the quasi-official organization in charge of civilian 
affairs between Taiwan and Mainland China, said in the message 
that the March 31 Qiandao Lake disaster and its mishandling by 
mainland authorities underscored the lack of an effective and 
immediate communication channel between the two sides when an 
accident occurs. 
  Amid public outrage and criticism over the incident in 
Taiwan, SEF said the two sides should hold talks to devise a 
formula for Taiwan-Mainland China travel security, and to build 
a safer environment for cross-strait travel. 
  In addition to the travel security issue, SEF, on May 25, 
proposed to hold negotiations with ARATS in early June on 
compensation for the 24 Taiwan tourists killed in the Qiandao 
Lake incident, but ARATS has yet to respond to the request. 

</TEXT>

