<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Deficit With EU Widens </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade Deficit With EU Widens </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2805142394 Taipei CNA in English 1335 GMT 28 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2805142394 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Liu Kun-yuan and Danielle Yang] </F>
  [Text] Madrid, May 27 (CNA) -- Taiwan registered its first 
four-monthly deficit ever with the European Union through April, 
according to customs statistics. 
  The trade deficit of US$40 million resulted from increasing 
imports from and decreasing exports to the EU, customs officials 
said. Taiwan registered a US$543 million trade surplus with the 
EU in the first four months of 1993. 
  During the January-April period, Taiwan imported US$3.596 
billion worth of products from the EU, a growth of 8.7 percent 
from the first four months of last year. Taiwan's exports to 
the area totaled only US$3.556 billion, a 7.7 percent decline, 
the statistics showed. 
  The US$7.153 billion in two-way trade between the two was a 
0.1 percent decline. 

</TEXT>

