<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jordan Seeks Reduction of Debt </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jordan Seeks Reduction of Debt </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3005084294 Taipei CNA in English 0651 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3005084294 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Debbie Kuo] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 30 (CNA) -- Jordan recently asked the 
Republic of China [ROC] to cut Jordan's foreign debt based on 
the spirit of the "Paris Club," of which the ROC is not a member. 
  Jordan asked Taipei to cut some U.S.$1 million from its debt 
after Taipei agreed to cancel 75 percent of Nicaragua's 
U.S.$22.84 million in loans with the island. 
  According to Ministry of Foreign Affairs officials, Jordan 
is 
not likely to be given the same treatment as Nicaragua. They 
said that Jordan's lack of diplomatic ties with Taiwan was the 
main reason which would prevent the foreign debt reduction. 
  Jordan received several loans from the ROC in the 1970s, but 
has been unable to repay the debt as planned because of 
financial difficulties. 
  News that Taipei agreed to cancel 75 percent of the debt 
owned it by Nicaragua during ROC President Li Teng-hui's visit 
to the Central American country early this month fueled a spate 
of inquiries from several debtor countries for similar 
treatment, the officials said. 
  About 30 countries owe money to the ROC. 
  The "Paris Club" or G10, was established in 1962 by then 10 
international monetary fund member countries. It aims to unify 
loan terms and accords for international debtor nations. Club 
members reduce the foreign debts for nations which are plagued 
with anemic foreign exchange reserves but have started economic 
reforms that would secure future loan payments. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

