<H3> <TI>   Taxation Pact With Vietnam Expected </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taxation Pact With Vietnam Expected </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2705140594 Taipei CNA in English 1333 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2705140594 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Bear Li] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 27 (CNA) -- Vietnam and Taiwan will 
soon sign an agreement on the avoidance of double taxation, Le 
Sinh Tang, new director of the Vietnam Economic and Cultural 
Office in Taipei, said Friday [27 May]. 
  "Negotiations are under way to remove the last and small 
obstacle to the proposed pact," Le, who assumed his post on May 
19, said. 
  Le, a former Hanoi vice mayor, said he expects trade and 
economic exchanges between his country and Taiwan, especially in 
tourism and agricultural and technological cooperation, will 
continue to increase. 
  Taiwan is currently the largest source of foreign investment 
in Vietnam, having pumped US$1.5 billion into the country as of 
the end of last month. Both nations earlier this year signed an 
investment- guarantee agreement. 
  The Vietnam Economic and Cultural Office was set up in 
Taipei 
early last year, with Dao Duc Chinh, a former Foreign Ministry 
official, as acting director. He is now serving as Le's deputy. 
  Le refused to comment on the possibility that Vietnamese 
Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet might visit Taiwan. 
  Vo, while taking part in the annual conference of the 
Pacific 
Basin Economic Council in Kuala Lumpur earlier this week said he 
would be willing to visit Taiwan if invited. 
  Le, however, said many obstacles would have to be removed 
before Vo could visit, given the absence of diplomatic relations 
between the two countries. 

</TEXT>

