<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-104 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Island Considers Voluntary Car Export Limits for Japan, ROK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Island Considers Voluntary Car Export Limits for Japan, ROK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3005141994 Taipei CNA in English 1342 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3005141994 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Bear Li] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 30 (CNA) -- Taiwan may ask Japan and 
South Korea to adhere to a self-imposed limit on car exports to 
the island after Taiwan opens its car market to foreign 
countries, economic officials said Monday [30 May]. 
  Taiwan, in a bid to join the General Agreement on Tariffs 
and 
Trade, is planning to open the car market by lowering tariffs, 
abolishing local content rate requirements and canceling 
existing bans on imports from certain countries. 
  But Taiwan will follow the example of the United States and 
the European Union and seek to reach "tacit agreements" with 
Japan and South Korea, asking them to voluntarily set quotas on 
their car exports to the island, 
  The officials explained that to ask a country which enjoys a 
surplus to sign such a voluntary restraint agreement is not in 
violation of the spirit of GATT. Japan had a trade surplus of 
U.S.$15 billion last year, while South Korea's was U.S.$1 
billion. 
  The government, in the meantime, will consider allowing 
foreign carmakers to set up production here in a bid to "force" 
the 11 local makers to streamline operations. Poorly performing 
local makers then would be phased out in the face of stronger 
competition brought in by the newcomers, they said. 
  The officials revealed that three foreign makers have 
contacted the ministry on the possibility of setting up plants 
in Taiwan. 
  According to an earlier assessment by the ministry, local 
makers' market share will fall to 30 percent from the existing 
50 percent after Taiwan enters GATT. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

