Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Crushes 20,000 Pirated Discs, Video Tapes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Crushes 20,000 Pirated Discs, Video Tapes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2805090894 Taipei CNA in English 0735 GMT 28 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2805090894 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Debbie Kuo] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 28 (CNA) -- More than 14,000 pirated 
video tapes and 6,000 laser discs were crushed Saturday [28 May] 
to mark the government's determination to end intellectual 
property rights (IPR) infringement in Taiwan. 
  The counterfeit tapes and discs, worth over NT [New Taiwan] 
$20 million (US$740,000), were destroyed in an annual IPR 
crackdown campaign sponsored by the Government Information 
Office, National Bureau of Standards, and the Copyrights 
Protection Committee of the Interior Ministry. 
  In a speech before the ceremonial destruction, Vice Interior 
Minister Yang Pao-fa said Taiwan is entering a "users pay" era 
after the country vowed to join the international community in a 
campaign to eliminate IPR and copyright infringement. 
  Yang said it is particularly important for Taiwan to observe 
IPR protection practices as the country is supposed to develop 
intellectual property rights protection relations with 118 
member nations of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade 
(GATT) upon joining the world trade regulatory body. 
  Yang urged the public to cooperate with the government in 
achieving the ambitious goal of making Taiwan a 
"counterfeit-free" country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

