<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rong Yiren Encourages State-Owned Enterprises </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rong Yiren Encourages State-Owned Enterprises </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2705160794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1457 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2705160794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jinan, May 27 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Vice-President 
Rong Yiren has urged major state-owned enterprises to orient 
themselves with the market and play a leading role in the market 
economy being created nationwide. 
  During a tour of inspection of east China's Shandong 
Province 
from May 19 to 26, Rong said that the establishment of a market 
economy has afforded an excellent opportunity for such 
enterprises to develop themselves. 
  The enterprises have strengths in personnel, technology and 
equipment, he said, noting that some have set an example for 
others to follow in displaying these advantages fully. 
  He expressed the belief that workers and staff of such 
enterprises will certainly brace up and work even harder to 
invigorate their enterprises. 
  Local officials told the vice president that during the 
first 
four months of 1994, output value of major state-owned 
enterprises all over Shandong Province shot up 15 percent over 
the same period in 1993. 
  Profits and taxes generated by such enterprises jumped 20 
percent during that period. 
  "Reform is essential to the invigoration of major 
state-owned 
enterprises," Rong told local officials. 
  Specifically, such enterprises must introduce a modern 
enterprise system and a market-oriented operational mechanism by 
carrying out reforms in employment, personnel and income 
distribution, he noted. 
  The leader also stressed the need to arouse the initiative 
of 
workers and staff, develop and manufacture quality and 
marketable products and pursue a diverse economy as a way to 
provide jobs to surplus workers. 
  He called for efforts to promote scientific and 
technological 
progress. He did so while visiting the Jinan Motorcycle Plant, 
the Qilu Petrochemical Corporation, the North Star Wristwatch 
Factory and seven other companies in seven cities, as well as 
two economic and technological development zones in the cities 
of Yantai and Weihai. 
  "When possible, major enterprises should set up their own 
research institutes," he said, adding that practice will make it 
possible to speed up the upgrading of products and improve their 
competitiveness. 
  According to the vice president, the import of funds and 
technology, especially high and new technology, is a good way to 
retool major state-owned companies in China. 
  Rong Yiren also asked such companies to make full use of 
domestic scientific and technological findings. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-24536 </DOCNO>
