Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Southeast Asia &amp; Pacific </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Peng, Malaysia's Mohamed Exchanges Letters on Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Li Peng, Malaysia's Mohamed Exchanges Letters on Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3005161194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1543 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3005161194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 30 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng 
and Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamed have expressed a 
strong desire to improve bilateral trade and economic 
cooperation. 
  The two prime ministers said this in a recent exchange of 
letters to mark the 20th anniversary of the establishment of 
diplomatic relations by China and Malaysia, Foreign Ministry 
sources said today. 
  Premier Li said that the cooperation between China and 
Malaysia had made rapid progress on the basis of the five 
principles of coexistence since the establishment of diplomatic 
ties on May 31, 1974. 
  Li said that Mahathir's three visits to China in recent 
years 
had served to promote bilateral understanding and mutual trust, 
and that the good relations between the two countries would 
benefit their peoples and be conducive to promoting regional 
peace, stability and prosperity. 
  Meanwhile, Prime Minister Mahathir said in his letter that 
the development of the good relations between Malaysia and China 
was due to the Chinese leaders being pragmatic and favoring 
openness. 
  He said that China's policy of good neighborliness had 
allowed bilateral relations to develop rapidly. He also 
expressed the belief that the two countries would widen their 
cooperation not only in the fields of the economy, trade and 
investment but also in tourism, cultural exchange and 
people-to-people contact. 
  Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen and his Malaysian 
counterpart Abdullah Ahmad Badawi also exchanged letters marking 
the 20th anniversary of the opening of formal relations. 

</TEXT>

