<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Visit of Former Soviet Prime Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Visit of Former Soviet Prime Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Ryzkov Arrives in Taipei </H4>

<F P=102> OW2705134694 Taipei CNA in English 1258 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2705134694 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Flor Wang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 27 (CNA) -- Nikolai I. Ryzkov, former 
prime minister of the now defunct Soviet Union, arrived in 
Taipei Friday [27 May] for a week-long visit. 
  Ryzkov, accompanied by his wife and a six-member party, is 
here at the invitation of the Republic of China [ROC] &amp; 
Russia 
International Association for Humanitarian Dialogue. 
  Cheng Po-chiu, West Asian affairs director of the Ministry 
of 
Foreign Affairs, officially greeted the Ryzkov delegation at 
Chiang Kai-shek International Airport. 
  Ryzkov, 65, who was first elected as secretary-general of 
the 
Soviet Communist Party by Mikhail Gorbachev in 1985 before being 
elevated to the post of prime minister, resigned in 1990 after 
objecting to the 500-day economic reform program launched by the 
Soviet Government. 
  During his stay here, Ryzkov will call on President Li 
Teng-hui, Premier Lien Chan, and Foreign Affairs Minister Chien 
Fu. He will also deliver a speech at the Legislative Yuan and 
hold seminars with local business leaders. 

</TEXT>

