<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hong Kong, May 27 (XINHUA) -- The American Chamber 
of Commerce in Hong Kong welcomes President Bill Clinton's 
decision to renew China's most-favored nation (MFN) trade status 
and delink human rights issues from the annual renewal of MFN. 
  "it is critically important to Asia -- the most dynamic and 
vital region on the face of the globe -- that our two countries 
have a relationship that works," the chamber said in a news 
release issued here this evening. 
  It noted that the president's statement of his intention to 
delink human rights issues from the annual renewal of MFN 
signals a firm commitment on the part of the American Government 
to rebuild a "functional, effective and wide-ranging bilateral 
relationship." 
  "The long and bitter debate over MFN is over at last," said 
Gerald Murdock, chairman of the chamber. 
  This is a time for "moderation and optimism," he said, 
adding 
"both the United States and China must seize the moment to build 
new ties, based on broader engagement and dialog." 

